## Server Components vs Client Components

### Server Component

```tsx
// app/conversations/page.tsx (Server Component by default)
export default async function ConversationsPage() {
  const conversations = await getConversations();  // Server-side fetch
  
  return (
    <div>
      {conversations.map(conv => (
        <ConversationCard key={conv.id} conversation={conv} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Client Component

```tsx
'use client';

import { useState } from 'react';

export function ConversationCard({ conversation }) {
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);
  
  return (
    <div onClick={() => setExpanded(!expanded)}>
      {conversation.title}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Data Fetching

### Server-Side Fetching

```tsx
// app/conversations/page.tsx
export default async function ConversationsPage() {
  const conversations = await fetch('https://api.omi.me/v1/conversations', {
    headers: {
      'Authorization': `Bearer ${token}`,
    },
  }).then(res => res.json());
  
  return <ConversationsList conversations={conversations} />;
}
```

### Client-Side Fetching

```tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export function ConversationsList() {
  const [conversations, setConversations] = useState([]);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch('/api/conversations')
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setConversations(data));
  }, []);
  
  return (
    <div>
      {conversations.map(conv => (
        <div key={conv.id}>{conv.title}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Best Practices

1. **Server Components**: Use for data fetching when possible
2. **Client Components**: Use for interactivity ('use client')
3. **API Routes**: Use for server-side logic
4. **Error Handling**: Handle errors gracefully
5. **Loading States**: Show loading indicators
6. **TypeScript**: Use TypeScript for type safety
7. **Environment Variables**: Use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix for client vars

